article.headline: Both teams score season lows
article.linkText: Taurasi scores only four, but UConn ousts Va. Tech
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Even as Connecticut's hurry-up offense
stalled, the Huskies' advanced to the semifinals of the Big East
tournament.

UConn ran into stubborn Virginia Tech defenders at every turn
before grinding out a 48-34 victory Sunday in a game in which each
team had a season-low point total.

"They did a great job taking us away from our stuff," UConn
coach Geno Auriemma said. "We could never get comfortable passing
and catching the ball. And after all that, you start to rush a bit.
Some of our problems were a little bit of impatience."

Barbara Turner scored 14 points and Jessica Moore added 11 for
the No. 4 Huskies (25-3), the regular season champs for the 11th
straight year.

UConn played the final seven minutes without Diana Taurasi, who
was sidelined with four fouls. She shot 2-for-10 and finished with
four points.

Virginia Tech made just five field goals in the second half, the
last two coming in the final 40 seconds. Carrie Mason led Virginia
Tech (22-7) with 13 points and was the only Hokie in double
figures. The Hokies' 34 points was two off an all-time tournament
low. It was also the second-lowest point total in school history
for Virginia Tech. The Hokies lost 66-33 in 1995 to Tennessee.

"We handled their defensive pressure pretty well, but could not
convert on the offensive end," Mason said.

UConn shot 18-for-56 (32 percent) from the field, while the
eighth-seeded Hokies finished 11-of-43 for 26 percent.

UConn won the previous meeting against Tech 68-50 in Blacksburg
in January. This time, the Hokies came out more aggressively on
defense, taking away UConn's passing lanes.

"We defended their tendencies much better than the first time
we played them this year," Tech coach Bonnie Henrickson said.

Neither team could hit a 3-pointer in the first half, going a
collective 0-for-10 from behind the arc. Maria Conlon's putback
with 8:48 remaining gave the Huskies their largest first-half lead
at 19-12. It was also their final field goal of the period. The
Huskies held a 21-14 lead at the break.

UConn finally found its range from the perimeter in the second
half, opening the period with a 10-2 run that Moore kicked off with
a pair of free throws and included 3-pointers from Conlon and Ann
Strother. The Huskies led by as many as 17 in the half.

"Whenever you come out in the second half, you always want to
make the first punch against the other team," Moore said. "We
just became really patient and started looking for each other. We
were able to regroup."

Virginia Tech mounted a 5-0 run, all on free throws late in the
half when Taurasi and Moore picked up their fourth fouls. The
Hokies pulled within nine at 38-29, but the Huskies countered with
eight straight points to put the game away.

UConn had the edge inside, outrebounding the Hokies 38-34.
Ashley Battle grabbed 10 boards for the Huskies, who outscored Tech
26-12 in the paint.

The Huskies, trying for their league-leading 10th tournament
title, will take on Boston College in a semifinal on Monday. The
Eagles advanced earlier Sunday with a 65-53 win over Miami.

UConn won nine straight tournament titles, a streak snapped last
year in the final by defending champ Villanova. The Wildcats also
ended UConn's NCAA-best 70-game win streak in that game.

The game was Virginia Tech's last appearance in the Big East.
The Hokies joined in 2000-01 and will enter the Atlantic Coast
Conference next season.
